<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Fri 24 Sep 2004
From: Henry L Niman, PhD <henry_niman@recombinomics.com>
Source: The Nation, Sat 25 Sep 2004 [edited]
<http://nationmultimedia.com/page.news.php3?clid=2&id=121420&usrsess=1>

Thailand: death of mother attributed to person to person transmission
---------------------------------------------------------------------
Thai health authorities are trying to find out whether a girl passed the
avian influenza A (H5N1) virus to her mother [and] aunt. They are anxiously
awaiting test results from [the mother] who died on Monday -- possibly from
avian influenza virus infection. They fear she could be the first case of
human to human [transmission of] infection. "This is quite a big issue and
crucial to confirming the existence of human to human infection [of avian
influenza]," said Dr Charal Trinwuthipong, acting permanent secretary of
the Public Health Ministry and director-general of the Disease Control
Department.
If test results confirm that the 26 year old woman [was infected by avian
influenza A (H5N1) virus], it means the virus has mutated and can be passed
from human to human, he said, adding that the woman had not been in contact
with infected animals. The woman fell ill and died in Nonthaburi about a
week after having close physical contact with her 11 year old daughter, who
died of symptoms similar to avian influenza virus infection on 12 Sep 2004,
Charal said. The girl died after a week in hospital. The mother was with
her the entire time, he said.
The girl's aunt was also ill with flu-like symptoms, he said, adding that
she had also not [been in contact with any] infected poultry. [Henry Niman
has added a note to indicate that the aunt is still alive].
Charal said the chances of detecting the H5N1 virus in the mother are
rather slim. Her body has already been injected with formalin. The girl had
not been listed as a suspected bird flu case until her mother died, said Dr
Wirat Phuthi-methee, Kamphaeng Phet's chief health officer.
The authorities have also unearthed another suspected case, a 13 year old
boy living in Khanu Woralak-saburi, the same district the girl lived in.
The boy died last Monday [21 Sep 2004], said Nakhon Sawan health chief
officer Dr Buares Sriprataksa. Wirat conceded that the 2 children had not
been listed as suspected cases earlier due to lax screening measures.
Hospitals might not have been aware they could have been infected with
avian influenza virus. Doctors failed to ask if they had been in contact
with dead chickens due to the fact their homes were not in designated bird
flu control areas.
Public health minister Sudarat Keyuraphan has now ordered all hospitals to
use comprehensive screening measures on every patient and to ask if they
had touched birds or lived in the areas where poultry had died. "We can no
longer just wait for updates of new control areas from the Livestock
Development Department]," she said. The minister will today lead a team of
health officials on a visit to Kamphaeng Phet. She also ordered urgent
disinfecting of areas in the province suspected of having the bird flu
virus. Test results of the 4 cases, except the girl, who has already been
cremated, are expected in 3 days.
[byline: Duangkamon Sajirawattanakul and Arthit Khwankhom]
--
Henry L Niman, PhD
<henry_niman@recombinomics.com>
[I am indebted to Nati Elkin <Elkin@poultrymed.com> for pointing out that
the WHO website currently lists 13 confirmed cases of avian influenza A
(H5N1) virus infection in Thailand, 9 of whom have died. If the 4 suspected
cases described above are confirmed the total would become 17, 12 of whom
have died.
<http://www.who.int/csr/disease/avian_influenza/country/cases_table_2004_09_0>
- Mod.CP]
