[2]
Date: Sat 25 Sep 2004
From: Henry L Niman, PhD <henry_niman@recombinomics.com>
Source: Channelnews asia.com, Agence France Presse report, Sat 25 Sep 2004
[edited]
<http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/afp_asiapacific/view/108462/1/.html>

Thailand: statement by WHO representative on possibility of human to human
transmission
--------------------------------------------------------
The World Health Organization said on Sat 25 Sep 2004 that it was
"suspecting human to human transmission" of avian influenza virus had
occurred in northern Thailand, marking what could be the first such
transmission of this virus. From the existing data we are suspecting human
to human transmission of avian influenza virus, WHO's acting Thailand
representative Kumara Rai told Agence France Presse after studying
information from Kamphaeng Phet province where the deaths of a girl and boy
are suspected to have been caused by avian influenza virus. The 11 year old
girl's mother, who lived near Bangkok but traveled north to visit her
daughter in hospital and then attend her funeral, returned to the Thai
capital where she too fell ill and died. Her death is also on the suspect list.
[Avian influenza A (H5N1) virus infection] is suspected but has not been
confirmed in these cases, and laboratory tests on the 3 fatalities, as well
as of the girl's aunt (who has been admitted to hospital with severe
pneumonia), were being conducted to determine whether they carried the
virus. Rai said the WHO was "very much concerned, but we are awaiting
laboratory confirmation", which is expected as early as Mon 27 Sep 2004. He
said he had contacted the UN health agency's headquarters in Geneva to urge
them to send experts to Thailand to assist in the field investigation.
The avian influenza A (H5N1) virus has killed 28 [29 according to WHO as of
9 Sep 2004 - Mod.CP] people in Vietnam and Thailand this year in 2 waves of
Asian outbreaks which also caused the death or culling of more than 100
million chickens. WHO fears H5N1 could mutate into a highly contagious form
that triggers a global human flu pandemic. When asked if a confirmed virus
leap between humans in the Thai cases would mark the first step in such a
feared mutation, Rai said "I think so." Health ministry officials have
confirmed the girl and the 13 year old boy in Kamphaeng Phet had come into
contact with their households' chickens that fell ill and died, but Rai and
others have said it was not clear whether the mother and the aunt had
contact with the animals. On Fri 24 Sep 2004 Rai met with field
epidemiologists, Thai-based officials from the US Centers for Disease
Control, and senior Thai health ministry officials to establish whether the
women had come into contact with fowl.
"We are still almost firm [sure? - Mod.SH] that there was no contacts with
sick birds," Rai said. Thailand has been put on full bird flu alert as a
precautionary measure, said health minister Sudarat Keyuraphan, who along
with other officials has acknowledged that concern has mounted that the
mother and aunt may have contracted bird flu directly from the girl.
Sudarat sought to downplay fears, stressing that preliminary tests on the
aunt had not confirmed avian influenza virus infection.
--
Henry L Niman, PhD
<henry_niman@recombinomics.com>
[It seems premature to conclude that person to person transmission of avian
influenza virus may have occurred, while it still has to be confirmed
unequivocally that avian influenza virus was responsible for the deaths of
any of the 3 deceased. Tests on the surviving patient appear to have been
negative so far. - Mod.CP
ProMED-mail is grateful to all who have sent us information about these
developments. We now await the definitive diagnosis, which we hope will be
available by Monday. Readers may find the Thai Ministry of Public Health
website of value
<http://thaigcd.ddc.moph.go.th/AI_case_report_240904.html>. - Mod.MPP/SH]
